The problem from what little I know about the law is this:

If I sign or passively agree to a liability waiver to not hold a second party responsible for some dangerous activity in which they are allowing or assisting me to participate Â– paintball (I have to sign a form), seeing a hockey game (the agreement occurs when the money changes hands Â– waiver is on the back of the ticket), eating rare beef (they now put warnings on the bottom of the menus). That waiver often does not stand up in court. It can actually be used against the second party, because it says the activity is dangerous and the second party is fully aware it is dangerous.

